<p>When looking at the top 4 candidates in this year’s running election, Facebook has identified the total spending rates for each candidate, taken from March of 2019 to today (via Facebook’s Ad Library). These numbers break down the idea that Trump has spent $26.9 million alone on Facebook, followed by Bernie at $13.3 million, then by Biden at $8.33 million (Guttmann).  These numbers reveal the spending by each candidate on Facebook alone, showing clearly that there is an incredible amount of political advertising that goes into marketing on Facebook.  Meaning, there has to be a reason why these candidates are consistently putting so much money into marketing to the public, right? Through the usage of Facebook advertising techniques, as well as their own personal techniques taken place through attacking posts, politicians are able to use the personal information given on a user and strategically place their advertisements to increase voting.  Whether this happens ethically or unethically, politicians everywhere finally understand the power of social media, and are doing anything they can to use it.</p>


<p>Politicians everywhere are forming stronger connections with Facebook and its Ad Library, as well as establishing sturdy relationships within its community, as Facebook is taking over how advertising has originally been structured. Even just 15 years ago, the structure and purpose of advertising has drastically changed, while today more politicians than ever are directly targeting those who fit their ideal image of who they want to have vote for them (Brader).  Through the generally recent trend of social media usage, politicians have been slowly catching on to the importance social media, like Facebook, has to offer.  This shift from physical advertisements (such as newspapers) to digital advertisements (such as Facebook and Instagram) is causing one of the greatest boosts in marketing history (Hwang).  With this evolution comes integrations and improvements in the advertisement industry, specifically the ease of analyzing likes and followers of Facebook users.  Information is now found at the ease of a politician with the click of a button.  This information is quickly sold to industries, campaign offices, and people for, in politicians’ cases, better voter turnout. It is simple to discover demographics ranging from age and name to emotional and mental status (Baumgartner).  These advertisements can directly target users, usually targeting the correct users due to psychological effects, to allow politicians to always feel a sense of accomplishment.</p>

<p>There are numerous psychological factors that digitally come into play as to why certain ads seem tailored to you, as well as why a user may specifically be interested in the types of ads being shown.  Through psychological effects such as hate advertisements, supportive advertisements, or even just regular unbiased advertisements, politicians and marketers are able to analyze which of these tactics persuade and sway you into a particular direction. Ads are shaped to target based on likes, searches, interests and mutual followers.  These characteristics of Facebook are persuasion techniques that are not in the form of an ad, but greatly benefit the politician using and paying for your information (Brader).  Facebook takes a user’s specific likes and interests and compares to profiles similar, therefore the algorithm correctly predicts what ad a user would “randomly” be interested in.  With this type of technique, Facebook takes this kind of information and uses it to a disadvantage to target with ads someone would be persuaded by. This information is then bought by politicians and is the reason why some ads may seem more personable than others.</p>

<p>By Facebook using information from users’ likes as well as the likes from the mutual followers shared, data hubs can take users’ personal data and compare their actual personality with the digital personality that users have created only via the internet.  In other words, Facebook can determine the type of person someone is through information such as how long one hovered the mouse over an ad, how often one clicks categorical ads or posts, reaction to posts, which followers have the most likes from users, etc. (Auter).  Compiling information such as this only betters the chance that politicians can accurately target the correct users for specific advertisements paid for. Isn’t it crazy how Facebook statistically knows more about you than your husband or wife will ever know?</p>

<p>Users on Facebook are connected whether they believe so or not.  Strangers are constantly recommended through “Suggested Friends.”  This may seem randomized, but through taking the similar data mentioned above, Facebook compares profiles and sells this information to politicians just to better chances of winning elections, changing biased voters’ opinions, etc.  For example, the Cambridge Analytica compiled the exact information from Facebook and was successfully able to bias voters to vote for Trump based off of demographics and information from millions of users (Holman).  This highlights explicitly how personal data can easily be used transcribed and manipulated only to benefit those higher.</p>

<p>One of the more fascinating things behind the concept of political ads is the idea that all personal information on the internet is never private, and how any personal information is essentially “up for grabs” in regard to politicians in this 2020 Presidential election.  With this in mind, one of the perspectives I wanted audiences to understand was the appreciation of how political advertisements are just “pop-up” advertisements waiting to be clicked on.  Through even having a Facebook account, whether one notices it or not, political advertisements are present, and the information taken from each click, hover, and action on one’s keyboard are immediately taken as crucial data for a candidate’s next target.  For part of my interactive project, I formed a video from the perspective of a Facebook user constantly getting targeted political advertisements.  I wanted to create a feeling of competition behind politicians to lure you into their advertisement (or in this case voting) and your data making them fight over who can persuade you the best.  Every 2-3 seconds, a new ad is added with a different politician.  Each ad consists of either hate or supportiveness shown towards a candidate, and roughly a minute long of invading advertisements on the feed of my personal Facebook page.  Below, you can click on the picture and it will directly bring you to the video.  As you watch, reflect and try to comprehend how this represents political invasion of social media, and the constant tracking of Facebook users.</p>

