<p>Through this unique perspective of targeting, the user regains awareness of how frequent these political ads are on Facebook.  For the past 10 years, it has been so invading to users’ privacy that Facebook felt obligated to form an “Ad Library,” a library that reveals a specific amount of demographic information regarding targeted audiences, in order to shape a sense of transparency with the users that feel targeted.  But what tactics are making this approach so successful, regardless of private information being constantly exposed?</p>

<p>The idea behind the “persuasion of politics” just focuses on the concept of political persuasion in general, as well as adding the idea of attitude change.  Through these political advertisements, there comes attitude change and change in bias because of the specific targeted users, that is why this is so crucial in swaying voters in 2016 and now the 2020 election.  This transitions into the idea of emotional tactics, those that are used to sway emotions based on psychological or personal connection towards an ad.  This is one of the more popular tactics, as it allows for easier manipulation of users when trying to change voters’ minds about a candidate.  Questioning and reflection by the users are common as only specific types of emotional tactics are used toward people who could easily be swayed (Baumgartner).  Through this, because everyone is connected on Facebook, this social network can almost put most voters more at stake because no information is considered private, and whether or not you think information is kept away, Facebook and advertising agencies will always prove you wrong.  Tying in the pop-up political Facebook video, this summarizes how immune users feel to this so called “invasion of privacy.” The commonality of this is seen through everyday social media, however Facebook and advertisements seen have made users feel as though there should be no worry to this issue, making persuading advertisements become even more persuasive.</p>

<p>In all, politicians are able to use personal information given on a user and strategically place their advertisements to increase voting.  Through diving deeper into the data received by Facebook about users, politicians can successfully execute persuasion techniques not necessarily through the ad itself, but with the data received by these corporations.  Though this is an invasion of privacy, users are still not aware, as this is a common scene amongst nearly all social media platforms. These uses of “persuasion politics” with the breach of users’ data are effective ways (such as emotional tactics and negative campaigning) to manipulate targeted audiences to vote for a politician.  As users who experience this version of targeting every day, whether it is noticed or not, the power behind the like button isn’t just the satisfaction of a post; it’s much more powerful than even we have ever imagined.</p>




